WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.800
Today, we're going to show you
how to build a DIY teleprompter

00:00:02.800 --> 00:00:04.178
that will let you
read out a script

00:00:04.178 --> 00:00:05.800
while you're looking
right at the camera.

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:12.600
[Music]

00:00:12.600 --> 00:00:13.680
Guys, believe it or not,

00:00:13.680 --> 00:00:15.800
almost everything
that we've said on this channel

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:18.180
has been without the use
of a teleprompter.

00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:19.880
Some of you may be
surprised to learn that,

00:00:19.883 --> 00:00:21.233
because in my first videos,

00:00:21.233 --> 00:00:24.200
I was awkwardly staring straight
at the camera, rarely blinking,

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:26.040
or interacting
with my surroundings.

00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:27.180
It was a struggle for a while.

00:00:27.190 --> 00:00:28.656
I'd like to think
I've gotten better,

00:00:28.660 --> 00:00:30.460
and don't need
to do that anymore.

00:00:30.460 --> 00:00:33.600
However, we are going to show
you how to build a teleprompter,

00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:35.500
because they can be very useful.

00:00:36.160 --> 00:00:37.020
Here's the basic idea.

00:00:37.020 --> 00:00:38.700
Using foam core, hot glue,

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:39.884
and a sheet of acrylic,

00:00:39.884 --> 00:00:42.478
we can help you make
a teleprompter that will fit

00:00:42.478 --> 00:00:44.100
to your camera and smartphone.

00:00:44.100 --> 00:00:45.670
So guys, a lot of YouTubers

00:00:45.670 --> 00:00:48.460
and a lot of people
on TV use teleprompters.

00:00:48.460 --> 00:00:50.000
They're incredibly useful.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:51.280
They make it really easy.

00:00:51.280 --> 00:00:52.600
If you have a lot
of bullet points,

00:00:52.600 --> 00:00:54.300
you've got to hit really fast.

00:00:54.740 --> 00:00:56.100
Well, you've got
to memorize that,

00:00:56.100 --> 00:00:57.960
unless you have a teleprompter.

00:00:57.960 --> 00:00:59.800
Teleprompters aren't
for every situation.

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:01.600
If you're acting
on stage, or screen,

00:01:01.600 --> 00:01:02.660
something like that,

00:01:02.660 --> 00:01:04.300
then you can't be looking
right at the camera,

00:01:04.300 --> 00:01:07.220
which is where the cues are
usually going to be scrolling.

00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:09.000
But for anything
where you're really trying

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.360
to just focus on the camera
itself, maybe vlogging,

00:01:12.360 --> 00:01:16.740
or showing a DIY video
that has a lot to say,

00:01:16.740 --> 00:01:17.840
it can really save a lot of time

00:01:17.840 --> 00:01:20.540
so you don't have to sit
and memorize lines forever.

00:01:20.540 --> 00:01:22.200
The supplies you'll need
to build this are

00:01:22.200 --> 00:01:23.330
actually very simple.

00:01:23.330 --> 00:01:24.962
We've got a sheet of acrylic.

00:01:24.962 --> 00:01:27.835
This is an 8x10 sheet I picked
up at the hardware store

00:01:27.835 --> 00:01:29.600
for like less than four bucks.

00:01:29.600 --> 00:01:31.358
We've got a sheet of craft foam.

00:01:31.358 --> 00:01:33.300
This stuff comes
from Hobby Lobby,

00:01:33.300 --> 00:01:34.390
costs about $1.50.

00:01:34.390 --> 00:01:35.800
This is the thickest
stuff they have.

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:37.500
You could get something
a little bit thinner,

00:01:37.500 --> 00:01:39.320
but I like it with
the thicker version.

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:40.940
We have a hot glue gun,

00:01:40.940 --> 00:01:42.680
pretty much any hot glue gun
is going to work.

00:01:42.688 --> 00:01:44.288
And then we also have foam core.

00:01:44.288 --> 00:01:46.290
This is the stuff
that's paper on the outside,

00:01:46.290 --> 00:01:47.940
and like a styrofoam middle.

00:01:47.940 --> 00:01:49.740
We've got a
clicking razor blade,

00:01:49.740 --> 00:01:51.340
very useful because
if it started get to dull,

00:01:51.342 --> 00:01:52.892
you can just break the tip off,

00:01:52.892 --> 00:01:54.194
and keep using the rest of it.

00:01:54.194 --> 00:01:55.767
Pencil, it's good
for marking things,

00:01:55.767 --> 00:01:56.967
and this piece of paper,

00:01:56.967 --> 00:01:58.800
which were actually
just going to fold,

00:01:58.800 --> 00:02:01.160
and use as a 45
degree angle guide.

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:03.800
The other things you're going to
need are a camera to film with,

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:06.388
and a smartphone to run
the teleprompter app.

00:02:06.388 --> 00:02:09.300
This app that I'm using is
the Parrot Teleprompter app.

00:02:09.300 --> 00:02:11.102
The Parrot Teleprompter
is a commercially

00:02:11.102 --> 00:02:13.860
available version of
what we're building today.

00:02:13.860 --> 00:02:16.100
It's a bit more sturdy than what
we are going to build today,

00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:17.900
but it cost quite
a bit more as well.

00:02:17.900 --> 00:02:18.969
The app however is free,

00:02:18.969 --> 00:02:22.060
so that's what we're going to
be using with our DIY version.

00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:23.000
Before we started this build,

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:24.964
I reached out to a friend
of mine named Brigham,

00:02:24.964 --> 00:02:27.100
who actually invented
the Parrot Teleprompter,

00:02:27.100 --> 00:02:28.300
and I asked him some questions

00:02:28.300 --> 00:02:30.680
about his design
and invention process

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:32.600
so we could know what
we were getting into.

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:35.900
So the design itself is
actually deceptively simple,

00:02:35.900 --> 00:02:37.600
but there are
some few basic things

00:02:37.600 --> 00:02:39.093
that you really
want to keep in mind

00:02:39.093 --> 00:02:40.800
when you're building
one of these to make

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:42.400
it actually flawless.

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:45.500
One of those things is the angle
of your acrylic to make sure

00:02:45.500 --> 00:02:47.800
that everything is actually
lining up correctly.

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:48.600
The other thing

00:02:48.600 --> 00:02:51.200
that you really need to take
into account is the vignette.

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:54.511
You don't want your camera lens
to catch the side of the box

00:02:54.511 --> 00:02:56.100
of the teleprompter itself.

00:02:56.100 --> 00:02:59.030
We're going to want to build
this custom to our camera

00:02:59.030 --> 00:02:59.960
and our phone.

00:02:59.960 --> 00:03:01.130
Every phone is going
to be different,

00:03:01.130 --> 00:03:02.800
a lot of cameras
are going to be different.

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:04.900
You can see,
this right here is the camera

00:03:04.900 --> 00:03:07.480
that our cameraman
Mark usually uses.

00:03:07.480 --> 00:03:10.000
He's currently using
our emergency backup camera,

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000
so we can see
his primary camera.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:12.600
Sorry, Mark.

00:03:12.600 --> 00:03:14.425
And so we have
to build onto this,

00:03:14.425 --> 00:03:16.039
so that it all works smoothly.

00:03:16.039 --> 00:03:16.900
So to start off,

00:03:16.900 --> 00:03:19.800
we're just going to cut some 4
inch strips of our foam core

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:21.050
that's a large enough size

00:03:21.050 --> 00:03:23.000
that we can cut it
down to what we need,

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.100
but we won't end up with
any pieces that are too small.

00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:28.500
The first piece that we're going
to want to cut out of these,

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:31.300
that's actually going to be part
of the body of the teleprompter

00:03:31.300 --> 00:03:33.700
is going to be the pieces
that hold our phone.

00:03:33.700 --> 00:03:35.336
This is going to be
the basic idea here

00:03:35.336 --> 00:03:36.800
is we're just going
to have a slit,

00:03:36.800 --> 00:03:40.300
a rectangular hole cut into this
that our phone fits in nicely,

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:41.700
and that's going
to hold it in place,

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:44.660
and just generally do
everything we want to in terms

00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:46.500
of keeping our hardware
where we need it.

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:53.960
[Music]

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:54.920
I measured correctly.

00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:55.900
That's actually quite snug.

00:03:55.900 --> 00:03:57.719
As you can see,
it's not falling out like that.

00:03:57.719 --> 00:03:59.376
That's pretty good thing,
and then trim this,

00:03:59.376 --> 00:04:01.150
I'm going to give myself
too much space here.

00:04:01.150 --> 00:04:02.400
It's not going to be this tall.

00:04:02.400 --> 00:04:03.550
This is just moving on,

00:04:03.550 --> 00:04:06.200
and now, we need to build
another one exactly like that.

00:04:07.740 --> 00:04:09.940
Got our two pieces
that hold the phone, however,

00:04:09.940 --> 00:04:11.840
with my particular phone,

00:04:11.840 --> 00:04:13.700
I have the camera
that sticks out.

00:04:13.700 --> 00:04:16.924
It's not quite flush
with the rest of the phone body,

00:04:16.924 --> 00:04:18.140
and I want it to fit

00:04:18.140 --> 00:04:21.910
just right so I'm actually going
to cut that notch out as well.

00:04:21.910 --> 00:04:23.300
I'm gonna show you why.

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:25.785
So you can see
here the width that

00:04:25.785 --> 00:04:27.997
the teleprompter text runs at,

00:04:27.997 --> 00:04:31.020
and we want to encase
it about that width,

00:04:31.020 --> 00:04:33.600
and so we want this side to get
in a little bit closer.

00:04:33.600 --> 00:04:35.700
But right now,
it's bumping into my camera.

00:04:35.700 --> 00:04:38.000
So I need to cut a notch
so it doesn't do that.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:41.360
[Music]

00:04:41.360 --> 00:04:42.580
How did I do?

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:44.100
Nice.

00:04:44.100 --> 00:04:46.840
[Music]

00:04:46.840 --> 00:04:49.100
So obviously, we're going
to cut these down to size.

00:04:49.100 --> 00:04:51.000
But the next step
is going to be to cut

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:53.000
some 45 degree angle slits
into the side,

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:55.700
that's going to be what holds
our acrylic piece in place.

00:04:56.320 --> 00:04:59.480
Piece of paper folded
across diagonally.

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:02.860
It should give us
a perfect 45 degree angle.

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:05.100
Here is where we're going
to want our piece of acrylic.

00:05:05.100 --> 00:05:06.414
We've got the piece of paper,

00:05:06.414 --> 00:05:08.000
and I'm just going
to set that right

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:11.100
onto the screen of the phone,
and then this line,

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:12.500
where we can mark.

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:15.900
Same thing on the other side.

00:05:16.380 --> 00:05:18.500
We've got our 45 degree
angle lines, and now,

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:20.600
we need to cut out a small slot,

00:05:20.600 --> 00:05:23.016
the same thickness
as our acrylic sheet.

00:05:23.280 --> 00:05:26.640
We have the lines drawn longer
than they needed to be.

00:05:26.640 --> 00:05:28.890
We don't need to have
this extend all the way down

00:05:28.890 --> 00:05:30.260
off of the foam core.

00:05:30.260 --> 00:05:32.000
We're going to have
it stopped right here,

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:34.500
a little bit above
the height of the phone.

00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:37.980
We can see that it's
maybe five millimeters

00:05:37.980 --> 00:05:39.980
above the height
of the phone screen,

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:41.000
and on the other end,

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.249
it doesn't need to extend
all the way to the end

00:05:43.249 --> 00:05:44.840
of the phone screen either.

00:05:44.840 --> 00:05:47.420
So we're just going to cut
it off right about here,

00:05:47.422 --> 00:05:48.384
and all the light

00:05:48.384 --> 00:05:51.100
from the phone will be shining
up this direction.

00:05:52.060 --> 00:05:55.200
This is actually an interesting
demonstration right here

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:57.757
about how exactly
a teleprompter works.

00:05:57.757 --> 00:06:00.700
So our camera will be
filming this direction.

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:02.000
So we'll have the lens

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:03.900
of the camera will be
about right here,

00:06:04.540 --> 00:06:05.400
filming out here.

00:06:05.400 --> 00:06:07.900
This is where the person
being filmed is.

00:06:07.900 --> 00:06:10.860
Phone screen is down
here pointing up.

00:06:10.860 --> 00:06:14.000
The acrylic is reflective,
but not as much as a mirror.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:15.725
So light coming
off of our phone,

00:06:15.725 --> 00:06:17.564
the text that's
being written on it,

00:06:17.564 --> 00:06:19.300
is going to bounce up.

00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:21.550
Some of it is going to go right
through the acrylic,

00:06:21.550 --> 00:06:24.740
and it's just going to keep
going that direction.

00:06:24.740 --> 00:06:27.690
But some of the light is going
to hit the acrylic pane,

00:06:27.690 --> 00:06:31.180
and at a 45 degree angle,
it's going to bounce off.

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:33.600
And remember, this is
where we are over here.

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:36.500
So we're going to be able to see
what's on the phone screen

00:06:36.500 --> 00:06:38.340
as it bounces off this way.

00:06:38.340 --> 00:06:40.080
But because of the angle,

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:42.300
the camera isn't going
to see any of that light.

00:06:42.300 --> 00:06:44.200
The phone isn't going
to bounce light

00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:46.300
off the acrylic this direction.

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:48.220
That just doesn't happen.

00:06:48.780 --> 00:06:51.500
It's only going to go either
straight through the acrylic,

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:54.500
or bounce off the 45 degree
angle out towards us.

00:06:54.660 --> 00:06:55.760
So a tip for you,

00:06:55.760 --> 00:06:57.400
if you're ever cutting
mat for something

00:06:57.400 --> 00:06:59.857
that needs to look really
really pretty, make sure

00:06:59.857 --> 00:07:01.258
that you're cutting inwards.

00:07:01.258 --> 00:07:03.650
You don't want to ever cut
outwards towards the mat

00:07:03.650 --> 00:07:05.000
you're going to be keeping.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:06.800
You might end up
with like a score mark

00:07:06.800 --> 00:07:07.800
that you don't want.

00:07:07.800 --> 00:07:08.500
In this case,

00:07:08.500 --> 00:07:11.200
it doesn't really matter,
but for future reference.

00:07:11.600 --> 00:07:14.900
So you cut towards the piece
that isn't going to matter.

00:07:16.820 --> 00:07:19.640
So now, to know what size
of acrylic we need,

00:07:19.640 --> 00:07:22.200
we're going to measure
the cuts we've already made.

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:24.847
Now, what we also have
to take into account is

00:07:24.847 --> 00:07:26.494
how far apart we want these,

00:07:26.494 --> 00:07:29.258
and again, that depends
on the phone you're using.

00:07:29.258 --> 00:07:32.700
So we'll start by just cutting
a 4 inch wide strip of acrylic,

00:07:32.700 --> 00:07:34.955
kind of like we did
with our pieces of foam core,

00:07:34.955 --> 00:07:37.400
and we'll then chop it down
to the right width after.

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:39.600
Cutting acrylic is
more like scoring

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:40.800
and breaking acrylic.

00:07:40.800 --> 00:07:42.800
You don't slice all
the way through it,

00:07:42.800 --> 00:07:46.100
you cut a deep enough line
that it's slightly weaker there,

00:07:46.100 --> 00:07:49.030
and then you snap it over
the corner of something sharp.

00:07:49.030 --> 00:07:52.000
All right, I've run several cuts
down through there,

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:52.647
and I mean,

00:07:52.647 --> 00:07:55.000
I haven't even cut 1/4
of the way through,

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.800
but it's enough weaker
that I can now take the acrylic,

00:07:57.800 --> 00:07:59.700
put it over the edge
of our bench here.

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:01.560
Very nice.

00:08:01.560 --> 00:08:03.200
And it just snaps pretty clean.

00:08:04.860 --> 00:08:06.260
So in theory,

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:09.040
this now fits into
the slot we just cut.

00:08:09.300 --> 00:08:12.860
So we want just a little bit
of extra acrylic on the sides,

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:15.100
so we can adjust
it as necessary.

00:08:15.100 --> 00:08:17.980
So I'm just lining up
with phone screen.

00:08:17.980 --> 00:08:23.900
[Music]

00:08:23.900 --> 00:08:24.760
Yeah.

00:08:24.760 --> 00:08:25.800
Unfortunately, acrylic

00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:29.400
over time will get scratches
and dust on it, unlike glass,

00:08:29.400 --> 00:08:31.300
but it is a lot easier to cut.

00:08:31.300 --> 00:08:34.000
[Music]

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:35.180
Yeah.

00:08:35.620 --> 00:08:37.300
We don't really need
any height above the top

00:08:37.300 --> 00:08:38.574
of the reflecting screen.

00:08:38.574 --> 00:08:39.900
So let's mark right there,

00:08:39.900 --> 00:08:42.600
and then cut both of these posts
off of that height.

00:08:42.600 --> 00:08:47.300
[Music]

00:08:47.300 --> 00:08:49.138
So if you have the tools for,

00:08:49.140 --> 00:08:51.440
and if you know
how to cut glass,

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:53.126
you could use a glass screen.

00:08:53.126 --> 00:08:55.300
It would last
a little bit longer,

00:08:55.300 --> 00:08:57.400
but acrylic is
very easy to cut,

00:08:57.400 --> 00:08:58.962
very easy to handle so...

00:08:58.962 --> 00:09:00.280
And it's cheap.

00:09:00.280 --> 00:09:02.840
Let's measure to put
a roof on to this.

00:09:02.840 --> 00:09:04.800
And before we start gluing
all the pieces together,

00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:06.449
there's one more step
we want to take.

00:09:06.449 --> 00:09:09.400
We talked about how we
wanted to avoid vignetting.

00:09:09.400 --> 00:09:11.500
That's when there's
something on the sides

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:13.300
that showing up on screen,

00:09:13.300 --> 00:09:14.200
and I'm simulating it

00:09:14.200 --> 00:09:16.399
by just giving myself
blinders at the moment.

00:09:16.399 --> 00:09:18.097
If these are
on the edge of the lens,

00:09:18.100 --> 00:09:19.740
and they're too far forward,

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:21.320
then you're going to see
them on the sides,

00:09:21.320 --> 00:09:23.320
and you're not trying
to record this.

00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:25.720
You just want it to be
there holding stuff.

00:09:25.727 --> 00:09:28.846
So to make sure that we
don't get any vignetting,

00:09:28.846 --> 00:09:30.740
any blocking of the visual,

00:09:30.740 --> 00:09:32.600
we're also going to cut
out just a little bit

00:09:32.600 --> 00:09:34.390
of a curve shape into these,

00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:37.900
to try and minimize
any accidental encroaching

00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:38.607
on the sides.

00:09:38.607 --> 00:09:39.372
There you go,

00:09:39.372 --> 00:09:41.630
and you normally will not see
that in movies,

00:09:41.630 --> 00:09:44.333
but a really easy example,
turn on your camera phone,

00:09:44.333 --> 00:09:46.100
and just put your hand
to the side.

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:47.200
You'll see it.

00:09:49.680 --> 00:09:52.720
In the situation like this,
less is more.

00:09:52.720 --> 00:09:54.020
Don't melt your phone.

00:09:54.020 --> 00:09:57.640
[Music]

00:09:57.640 --> 00:09:59.200
Let's measure for the back.

00:09:59.200 --> 00:10:02.000
[Music]

